Know your strengths: You work hard to finish anything you start. Has perseverance played out in your life this week?
Know your strengths: You work very well in a team. How you have demonstrated teamwork this week and how that has helped others.
Know your strengths: You believe that you can control your future. Consider how your belief in yourself and abilities worked for you this week.
Know your strengths: You are someone who likes to bring smiles to other people. How have you made yourself and others smile this week?
Know your strengths: You are kind and generous to everyone who crosses your path. Consider how your generosity towards others played out this week.
Know your strengths: You have a strong belief in the higher purpose. Consider how your spirituality has played out this week.
Know your strengths: You approach everything you do with excitement and energy. Consider how your zest for life has played out this week.
Know your strengths: You stop and take notice of the beauty in every day experiences. How has your ability to find beauty in life worked out for you this week?
Know your strengths: You donâ€™t shy away from a challenge. Consider how bravery has played out this week.

Know your strengths: You never let your personal feelings bias your decisions about other people. How has fairness played out this week?
Know your strengths: You never jump to conclusions without considering all sides. How has your open-mindedness played out for you this week?
Know your strengths: Other people think of you as wise and turn to you for advice. Consider how your perspective on a situation helped another person this week.
Know your strengths: You love learning new things, whether in a class or on your own. Consider how learning something new worked out for you this week.
Know your strengths: You prefer that your accomplishments speak for themselves rather than being in the spotlight. How has your humbleness worked out this week?
Know your strengths: You have a way of being able to read a situation and put people at ease. Consider how your awareness has helped another person this week.
Know your strengths: You are cautious and careful in everything you choose to do. Consider how the choices you have made worked out for you this week.
Know your strengths: You love to explore and discover new things. How has your love for adventures played out this week?
Know your strengths: Not only do you speak the truth but you live your life in a genuine way. Consider how your authenticity has played out this week.
Know your strengths: You excel at organizing group activities. Consider how your leadership has made something get done this week.
Know your strengths: You value close relationships with others, especially those you can count on. How have your friends and loved ones supported you this week?
Know your strengths: Your guiding principle is mercy and not revenge. Consider how compassion has played out for you this week.
Know your strengths: You never take anyone or anything for granted. Consider how your gratitude has played out for you this week.

You always finish what you start. What will you gain by quitting smoking?  Make a list.  How will it feel to accomplish these goals?
Consider how your quitting smoking contributes to making a better world.
Difficult situations will arise once you quit. Think about what situations will be hard for you. Write them down and create plans for how you can handle them.
Make at least one person smile each day - now and after you quit!
Picture the people in life that are important to you. Quitting smoking is an act of kindness not only to yourself but to others.
Difficult situations can arise while quitting smoking. Your strong sense of spirituality can serve as an important source of comfort.
Find new activities where you can have fun and be engaged without smoking.
Certain situations can be stressful when you quit smoking. Make a list of unfamiliar places you can visit that can remind you of all of the beauty in life.
If you are doubting your ability to quit smoking, remind yourself of other challenges you have faced successfully.  Why should quitting smoking be any different?
Plan at least 2 activities during the first week of quitting that allow you to be creative like painting, gardening, writing, or another hobby.
Take time to think about how quitting smoking is good not just for you and your health but also for others around you and for those who care most for you.
If you are wavering on your ability to quit smoking, consider all of the evidence that proves you can do it!

Attend a lecture at a local college or school about health-related risks of smoking.
